The time after the aircraft passes directly overhead before the sonic boom is heard is  

\[
t = \frac{h}{c}\sqrt{1-\frac{1}{M^{2}}}
\]

where  

* \(h = 8000\ \text{m}\) (altitude)  
* \(c = 340\ \text{m/s}\) (speed of sound at that altitude)  
* \(M = 1.75\) (Mach number).

\[
\begin{aligned}
\sqrt{1-\frac{1}{M^{2}}} &= \sqrt{1-\frac{1}{1.75^{2}}}
= \sqrt{1-\frac{1}{3.0625}}
= \sqrt{0.6734694}
\approx 0.8207 \\[4pt]
t &= \frac{8000}{340}\times 0.8207
\approx 19.3\ \text{s}
\end{aligned}
\]

Rounded to the nearest integer, the delay is **19 seconds**.

